{{wikipedia}}
==English==

===Etymology===
Borrowed, in the 19th century, from Vedic Sanksrit, to apply to nomadic groups thought to have spread across Western Eurasia, speaking a [[Proto-Indo-European]] language. The word is ultimately derived from ''[[Arya]]'' meaning ''[[noble]]''.

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɛəriən|-ɛəriən]]

===Homophones===
* [[Arian]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A member of any of the many nomadic peoples who are thought to have traveled throughout Western Eurasia spreading a [[Proto-Indo-European]] language. Some linguists and historians dispute the existence of the Aryans as a completely distinct group.
# {{cattag|used by Nazis}} A member of a (mythical) [[master race]], supposed to have originated in Scandinavia, which included Germans and other people of Nordic stock.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# {{cattag|No longer in technical use}} Of or pertaining to [[Indo-European]]s or Aryan peoples, cultures and languages.
# Pertaining, in Nazi propaganda and racialist theories, to the mythical Aryan [[master race]].

{{rfv-sense}} 
# Pertaining to Nazi propaganda and racialist theories.

